com.ca.mas.messaging

Interface MASPayload

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    MASMessage

    public interface MASPayload

    MASPayload describes the message format that is passed between MAS clients. The payload is a simple JSON document consisting of 8 key/value pairs;

    • Version - currently 1.0.
    • SenderID - a unique identifier typically registered with the corporate system.
    • SenderType - any defined sender such as 'User', 'Device', 'Application', etc. Whatever has meaning in the application's context.
    • DisplayName - a free-form value that contains the user friendly name for display.
    • SentTime - the number of milliseconds since the epoch.
    • ContentType - the IANA MIME media type.
    • ContentEncoding - the payload encoding such as base64 or UTF-8.
    • Payload - the opaque payload that is described by the content type and content encoding. This could be any set of bytes such as a text message, an image, etc. and is Base64 encoded

    This payload is opaque to the message broker and the format is MAS SDK specific. There is no expectation within the message broker of format or content. It is simply a byte stream.


    From the design document the payload should be of the form: 

          {
          "Version":"1.0",
          "SenderId":"user id",
          "SenderType":"USER",
          "DisplayName":"User Name",
          "SentTime":1438386369,
          "ProcessedTime":1446600366,
          "ForwardedTime":1446600373,
          "ContentType":"text/plain",
          "ContentEncoding":"base64",
          "Payload":"QWxsIHlvdXIgYXBpJ3MgYXJlIGJlbG9uZ3MgdG8gdXMh"
      }

      • setPayload

        void setPayload(byte[] payload)
        Description: This payload is a byte stream that is meaningful to the receiving client. The message broker passes this information through along with the rest of the MASMessage. The maximum size of the payload is system dependent and is not limited by the MAS SDK. If there are enough resource to handle this message then it considered to be a valid size.
        Parameters:
        payload - - the data part of the MASMessage

      • getPayload

        byte[] getPayload()
        Description: This payload is a byte stream that is meaningful to the receiving client. The message broker passes this information through along with the rest of the MASMessage. The client will use the content type and encoding type to interpret the received byte stream.
        Returns:
        byte[] the arbitrary bytes. Should not be null or there is no payload to transmit.

      • createJSONStringFromMASMessage

        java.lang.String createJSONStringFromMASMessage(android.content.Context context)
                                         throws MASMessageException
        Description: This method takes the entire MASPayload attributes and create a Base64 encoded version of the JSON document representing the payload. For example, this interface results in the JSON document; 
             {
      "Version":"1.0",
      "SenderId":"me",
      "SenderType":"USER",
      "SentTime":1457383162000,
      "ContentType":"text/plain",
      "ContentEncoding":"utf8",
      "Payload":"U29tZSBwYXlsb2FkIG1lc3NhZ2U="
      }

        Note that the inner payload is base64 encoded.
        Returns:
        String representing the base64 encoded JSON document.
        Throws:
        MASMessageException

      • createMASMessageFromJSONString

        void createMASMessageFromJSONString(java.lang.String jsonStr)
                             throws MASMessageException
        Description: This method takes a JSON object that has been turned into a String and attempts to turn it into a MASPayload object. This is a re-serialization of the transmitted MASPayload.
        Parameters:
        jsonStr - the JSON object, as a String, representing the MASPayload.
        Throws:
        MASMessageException - if the String cannot be converted or is not valid JSON.
